==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prophecy
<hw>Proph"e*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it></plu>
<plw>Prophecies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, <ety>[OE. <ets>prophecie</ets>, OF.
<ets>profecie</ets>, F. <ets>proph⟦eacute⟧tie</ets>, L.
<ets>prophetia</ets>, fr. Gr. <ets><?/</ets>, fr. <?/ to be an
interpreter of the gods, to prophesy, fr. <?/ prophet. See
<er>Prophet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A declaration of something to
come; a foretelling; a prediction; esp., an inspired
foretelling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hearkens after <qex>prophecies</qex> and dreams.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prophecy</qex> came not in old time by the will of man.</q>
<rj><qau>2. Pet. i. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>A book of prophecies; a
history; <as>as, the <ex>prophecy</ex> of Ahijah</as>.</def> <rj><au>2
Chron. ix. 29.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Public interpretation of Scripture; preaching;
exhortation or instruction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prophesier</ent>⟦br⟧
